<h2>Understanding Australian Website Accessibility Requirements</h2><br>

<p>Australia follows the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.1, which are internationally recognised standards for digital accessibility. Under the Disability Discrimination Act 1992, Australian businesses have legal obligations to ensure their digital services are accessible to people with disabilities.</p>

<h3>Legal Framework and Compliance Levels</h3><br>

<p>The Australian Government mandates WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance for government websites, and while private businesses aren't legally required to meet specific standards, the Human Rights Commission has ruled in favour of accessibility in several high-profile cases.</p>

<p>WCAG guidelines are organised around four key principles:</p>

<p>- <strong>Perceivable</strong>: Information must be presentable in ways users can perceive
<ul>
<li><strong>Operable</strong>: Interface components must be operable by all users</li>
<li><strong>Understandable</strong>: Information and UI operation must be understandable</li>
<li><strong>Strong</strong>: Content must be strong enough for various assistive technologies</p></li>
</ul>

<p>For Western Sydney businesses, aiming for Level AA compliance provides excellent protection while delivering measurable SEO benefits.</p>

