<h2>The SEO-Accessibility Connection: Why Google Loves Accessible Websites</h2><br>

<p>Here's where things get interesting for business owners: accessible websites consistently rank higher in search results. This isn't coincidence—it's by design.</p>

<h3>Shared Principles That Drive Results</h3><br>

<p>Search engines and assistive technologies both need to understand your website's structure and content. When you optimise for one, you're automatically improving the other:</p>

<strong>Semantic HTML Structure</strong>: Screen readers handle using heading hierarchies (H1, H2, H3). Google's algorithms use these same structures to understand your content organisation and topic relevance.

<strong>Alternative Text for Images</strong>: Alt text helps vision-impaired users understand images through screen readers. Google uses this same text to understand image content for image search rankings.

<strong>Clear Navigation</strong>: Users with cognitive disabilities benefit from consistent, logical navigation. Search engines use navigation structure to understand site hierarchy and distribute page authority. This is a core principle of our <a href="/mobile-first-responsive-design/">mobile-first responsive design</a> approach.

<strong>Fast Loading Times</strong>: Users with slower internet connections or older assistive technologies need fast-loading pages. Google's Core Web Vitals directly impact search rankings.

